U-Haul Data

Picture of Trucks

10' Truck: Studio to 1 Bedroom Apt.

15' Truck: 1 Bedroom Home to 2 Bedroom Apt.

20' Truck: 2 Bedroom Home to 3 Bedroom Apt.

26' Truck: 3 Bedroom Home to 4 Bedroom Home

10' Truck

We have 378 cities/MSAs and therefore 142,884 possible city combinations. I remove the combinations where the origin and destination city are exactly the same, leaving us with 142,506 combinations. I generated distributions of key variables related to 10' Trucks for these combinations. In particular, I looked at trip price, trip mileage, and number of days included. The modal price is just shy of $1,000, the modal mileage is just about $1,000 and the modal number of days is 5. Each distribution has a long right tail.

uhaul <- all1[all1$truck_type == "10' Truck" & all1$to != all1$from,]

par(mfrow = c(1, 2))
hist(uhaul$trip_price_1, breaks = 50, main = "Trip Price", ylab = "Frequency", xlab = "")
hist(uhaul$miles_included, breaks = 50, main = "Miles Included", ylab = "Frequency", xlab = "")
par(mfrow = c(1, 1))
plot(table(uhaul$days_included), main = "Days Included", ylab = "Frequency")

Next, I plotted trip mileage vs trip price. I color coded trips that take an odd (even) number of days red (blue). There is substantial variation in price over different levels of mileage, but there are clear "streaks" or pattern that emerge. I select the trips that are expected to take 7 days to take a closer look.

plot(uhaul$miles_included, uhaul$trip_price_1,
     col = alpha(ifelse(uhaul$days_included %% 2 == 0, "DodgerBlue", "tomato"), .01), pch = 19)
abline(v = c(min(uhaul$miles_included[uhaul$days_included == 7]),
             max(uhaul$miles_included[uhaul$days_included == 7])),
       col = alpha("black", .3),lty = 2, lwd = 2)

Something interesting about these top six trips is that these are the most expensive trips in the entire dataset - even moreso than trips almost two times as long. Further, there exist trips of two days that are more expensive than these bottom six trips. It does not appear that mileage is the most important factor to U-Haul.

An interesting feature of the data is the lack of symmetry in trip pricing. Like the example you used in your email, the price to go from LA to Dallas is different than the price from Dallas to LA. I investigate this by finding the difference in price between every symmetric trip.

diff <- uhaul$trip_price_1 - uhaul$trip_price_1[match(paste0(uhaul$from, "_", uhaul$to), paste0(uhaul$to, "_", uhaul$from))]
p1 <- uhaul$trip_price_1
d1 <- uhaul$miles_included
t1 <- paste0(uhaul$from, " to ", uhaul$to)

p1 <- p1[diff >= 0]
d1 <- d1[diff >= 0]
t1 <- t1[diff >= 0]
diff <- diff[diff >= 0]

p1 <- p1[order(-diff)]
d1 <- d1[order(-diff)]
t1 <- t1[order(-diff)]
diff <- diff[order(-diff)]

p1 <- p1[1:(length(diff) - (sum(diff == 0)/2))]
d1 <- d1[1:(length(diff) - (sum(diff == 0)/2))]
t1 <- t1[1:(length(diff) - (sum(diff == 0)/2))]
diff <- diff[1:(length(diff) - (sum(diff == 0)/2))]

In the data, only 2.61% of routes have symmetric prices. Below I plot the distribution of the price differences with and without these 2.61%. Next, I plot the more expensive trip on the x-axis and the cheaper on the y. I then plot the the more expensive trip vs the difference. Finally, I print the distance vs the price difference.

par(mfrow = c(1,2))
plot(table(diff), main = "Price Difference", xlab = "", ylab = "Frequency")
plot(table(diff[diff>0]), main = "Price Difference (excluding 0's)", ylab = "Frequency", xlab = "")
par(mfrow = c(1,1))

plot(p1, p1 - diff, pch = 19, col = alpha("MediumSeaGreen", .01),
     main = "", xlab = "Price", ylab = "Price Reverse")
abline(0, 1)

plot(p1, diff, pch = 19, col = alpha("MediumSeaGreen", .01),
     main = "", xlab = "Price", ylab = "Price Difference")
abline(0, 1)

plot(d1, diff, pch = 19, col = alpha("MediumSeaGreen", .01),
     main = "", xlab = "Distance", ylab = "Price Difference")
abline(0, 1)

Below are the trips with the largest price differences in total. It seems that U-Haul wants to keep people out of Cape Girardeau at all costs, for whatever reason. Below is a Google Maps screenshot of where this city is located. It is hillariously at the centroid of Memphis, Nashville and St. Louis.

I ran some basic regressions to look at how miles influneces price, even though clearly there is more at work. Surprisingly, FE do not change the relationships all that much. Rather, I think it has to do with the relativity between the two cities. For example: going from city A to city B might only matter insofar that A is more (less) desireable than B. This model is assuming the overall, "global" desireability of A and B matter, and I am not convinced that this is the case.

reg1 <- lfe::felm(trip_price_1 ~ miles_included, data = uhaul)
reg2 <- lfe::felm(trip_price_1 ~ miles_included + I(miles_included^2), data = uhaul)
reg3 <- lfe::felm(trip_price_1 ~ miles_included + I(miles_included^2) + I(miles_included^3), data = uhaul)
reg4 <- lfe::felm(trip_price_1 ~ miles_included + I(miles_included^2) + I(miles_included^3) | to + from, data = uhaul)

stargazer::stargazer(reg1, reg2, reg3, reg4,
                     type = "text",
                     add.lines = list(c("To / From FE", "No", "No", "No", "Yes")),
                     omit.stat = c("ser", "f"))

In the next two regressions, I try to explain the price difference between two routes rather than the price for a single route. I think is an interesting way to think about what we are trying to do. For example, I think this regression would benefit most from a variable that measures the difference in the economic freedom index (or whatever measurement) between the two cities.

str <- unlist(strsplit(t1, " to "))
from1 <- str[c(T,F)]
to1 <- str[!c(T,F)]
reg5 <- lfe::felm(diff ~ d1 + p1)
reg6 <- lfe::felm(diff ~ d1 + p1 | from1 + to1)
stargazer::stargazer(reg5, reg6,
                     type = "text",
                     add.lines = list(c("To / From FE", "No", "Yes")),
                     omit.stat = c("ser", "f"))
